Certainly! Creating a realistic HTML form that mimics a typical phishing setup is a great way to enhance the educational impact of your training module. Below is a detailed example of an HTML form that requests sensitive information, such as a social security number. This form includes styling to make it look authentic and includes placeholders to guide the user through the process.

### Example: Phishing Form Requesting Social Security Number

#### HTML Code:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Social Security Verification</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
        }
        .container {
            background-color: #fff;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            width: 100%;
            max-width: 400px;
        }
        h2 {
            text-align: center;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        .form-group {
            margin-bottom: 15px;
        }
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-bottom: 5px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        input[type="text"], input[type="password"] {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 8px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }
        input[type="submit"] {
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
            width: 100%;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }
        input[type="submit"]:hover {
            background-color: #45a049;
        }
        .footer {
            text-align: center;
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-size: 0.8em;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Social Security Verification</h2>
        <p>Please enter your social security number to verify your identity.</p>
        <form action="https://example.com/submit" method="POST">
            <div class="form-group">
                <label for="socialSecurityNumber">Social Security Number:</label>
                <input type="text" id="socialSecurityNumber" name="socialSecurityNumber" placeholder="Enter your Social Security Number" required>
            </div>
            <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        </form>
        <div class="footer">
            <p>If you did not request this verification, please contact us immediately.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure**:
   - **Container**: A div with a class `container` that holds the entire form and provides a clean layout.
   - **Form**: A form element with an action attribute pointing to a hypothetical submission URL (`https://example.com/submit`) and a method of `POST`.
   - **Fields**: 
     - **Label**: A label for each input field.
     - **Input Fields**: 
       - **Social Security Number**: A text input field where the user enters their social security number.
   - **Button**: A submit button to submit the form.

2. **Styling**:
   - **Body**: Centered content with a light background.
   - **Container**: A centered, styled container with padding and rounded corners.
   - **Form Group**: Margin and padding for spacing between fields.
   - **Labels**: Bold and aligned at the top of each input field.
   - **Inputs**: Styled with padding, borders, and rounded corners.
   - **Submit Button**: Styled with a green background and hover effect.
   - **Footer**: A footer with a disclaimer to encourage users to verify the request.

### Educational Impact:
- **Realism**: The form looks professional and similar to legitimate forms, making it harder for users to spot the phishing attempt.
- **Interactive Learning**: Users can interact with the form, entering data and submitting it, which helps them understand the potential risks.
- **Verification**: The form includes a disclaimer to encourage users to verify the legitimacy of the request, reinforcing good cybersecurity practices.

By using this example, you can create a realistic and engaging phishing simulation that effectively trains your employees to recognize and avoid phishing attempts.

